{{Infobox mountain |name = Agathla Peak |other_name = {{unbulleted list|{{spell-nv|Aghaałą́}} {{Nv icon}} |{{lang|es|El Capitan}} {{Link language|es}}}} |photo = Agathla Peak 2016.jpg |elevation_ft = 7099 |elevation_ref = {{NAVD88}}<ref name="pb">{{cite peakbagger |pid=3917 |name=Agathla Peak, Arizona |accessdate=October 19, 2008}}</ref> |prominence_ft = 1436 |prominence_ref = <ref name="pb"/> |location = {{unbulleted list | [[Navajo Reservation]] | [[Navajo County, Arizona|Navajo County]], [[Arizona|Arizona, U.S.]] }} |range = |coordinates = {{coord|36.826246928|N|110.225252542|W|type:mountain_region:US-AZ_scale:100000_source:GNIS|format=dms|display=inline,title}} |range_coordinates = |coordinates_ref = <ref name="ngs">{{cite ngs |pid=GP0629 |name=Agathla Peak Cairn |accessdate=2016-08-12}}</ref> |topo = [[United States Geological Survey|USGS]] Agathla Peak |type = [[Erosion|eroded]] [[volcanic plug]] |volcanic_field = Navajo Volcanic Field |first_ascent = |easiest_route = }}
'''Agathla Peak''' ({{lang-nv|Aghaałą́}}, {{lang-es|link=no|El Capitan}}) is a peak south of [[Monument Valley]], [[Arizona]], which rises over 1500 feet (457 meters) above the surrounding terrain. It is {{convert|7|mi}} north of [[Kayenta, Arizona|Kayenta]] and is visible from [[U.S. Route 163]]. The English designation ''Agathla'' is derived from the Navajo name ''{{spell-nv|aghaałą́}}'' meaning 'much wool', apparently for the fur of antelope and deer accumulating on the rock.<ref name=gnis>{{cite gnis|id=502|name=Agathla Peak|accessdate=October 19, 2008}}</ref> The mountain is considered sacred by the Navajo.
Agathla Peak is an [[Erosion|eroded]] [[volcanic plug]] consisting of [[volcanic breccia]] cut by [[Dike (geology)|dikes]] of an unusual igneous rock called [[Lamprophyre|minette]]. It is one of many such volcanic [[diatreme]]s that are found in Navajo country of northeast Arizona and northwest New Mexico. Agathla Peak and [[Shiprock]] in New Mexico are the most prominent. These rocks are part of the Navajo Volcanic Field, in the southern [[Colorado Plateau]]. Ages of these minettes and associated more unusual igneous rocks cluster near 25 million years.
[[File:Map of the Navajo Volcanic Fields.jpg|thumb|right|The Navajo Volcanic Field with Aglatha Peak]] [[File:Aerial view of Agathla peak with Monument Valley road (163) in the foreground.JPG|thumb|none|400px|Aerial view of Agathla peak with the road to Monument Valley (163) in the foreground]]
