{{For|the British/Canadian computer scientist|Timothy C. Lethbridge}}
{{good article}} {{EngvarB|date=August 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox person |name = T. C. Lethbridge |image = File:Thomas Charles Lethbridge.jpg |image_size = |caption = |birth_name = |birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1901|3|23}} |birth_place = [[Timberscombe]], [[Somerset]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|1971|09|30|1901|3|23|df=y}} |death_place = [[Exeter]], [[Devon]] |death_cause = |resting_place = |resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} --> |nationality = English |citizenship = United Kingdom |other_names = T. C. Lethbridge |known_for = ''The Power of the Pendulum'' |education = [[Wellington College (Berkshire)|Wellington College]], [[Cambridge University]] |alma_mater = |employer = [[University of Cambridge]] |occupation = [[Exploration|Explorer]], [[archaeology|archeologist]], and [[Parapsychology|parapsychologist]] |years_active = |home_town = |title = |salary = |networth = |height = |weight = |term = |predecessor = |successor = |party = |opponents = |boards = |spouse = |partner = |children = |parents = |relations = |callsign = |signature = |website = |footnotes = }}
'''Thomas Charles Lethbridge''' (23 March 1901 – 30 September 1971), better known as '''T. C. Lethbridge''', was an English [[archaeologist]], [[parapsychology|parapsychologist]], and [[exploration|explorer]]. A specialist in [[Anglo-Saxon archaeology]], he served as honorary Keeper of Anglo-Saxon Antiquities at the [[Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology, University of Cambridge|Cambridge University Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology]] from 1923 to 1957, and over the course of his lifetime wrote twenty-four books on various subjects, becoming particularly well known for his advocacy of [[dowsing]].
Born in [[Somerset]] to a wealthy family, Lethbridge was educated at [[Trinity College, Cambridge]], during the course of which he attended an expedition to [[Jan Mayen]] island, becoming part of the first group to successfully climb the [[Beerenberg]]. After a failed second expedition to the [[Arctic Circle]], he became involved in archaeology. In his capacity as Keeper of Anglo-Saxon Antiquities at the Cambridge University Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology, Lethbridge carried out [[Excavation (archaeology)|excavations]] at various sites around Britain. His claims regarding the existence of [[Iron Age Britain|Iron Age]] [[hill figure]]s on [[Wandlebury Hill]] in [[Cambridgeshire]] caused significant controversy within the archaeological community, with most archaeologists believing that Lethbridge had erroneously misidentified a natural feature. Lethbridge's methodology and theories were widely deemed unorthodox, and in turn he became increasingly critical of the archaeological profession.
After resigning from the university museum in 1957, Lethbridge moved with his wife to [[Branscombe]], [[Devon]]. There he devoted himself to researching [[paranormal]] phenomena, publishing a string of books on the subject aimed at a popular rather than academic audience. Most of this involved his research into the use of [[pendulum]]s for dowsing, although in other publications he championed the [[witch-cult hypothesis]] of [[Margaret Murray]], articulated the [[Stone Tape]] theory as an explanation for [[ghost]] sightings, and argued that [[Ancient astronaut hypothesis|extraterrestrial species were involved in shaping human evolution]]; in this he came to embrace and perpetuate the [[Western esotericism|esoteric]] ideas of the [[Earth mysteries]] movement. Although his work in parapsychology was derided and ignored as [[pseudoscience|pseudo-scientific]] by the academic establishment, he attracted a cult following, and his work was posthumously championed by esotericists like [[Colin Wilson]] and [[Julian Cope]]. In 2011 he was made the subject of a biography by Terry Welbourn.
==Early life==
===Youth: 1901–21=== Thomas Charles Lethbridge was born on 23 March 1901.{{sfnm|1a1=Anonymous|1y=1972|1p=448|2a1=Welbourn|2y=2011|2p=19}} His parents, Violet Lethbridge (née Murdoch) and her husband Ambrose Lethbridge, were wealthy and lived at Knowle House in [[Timberscombe]], Somerset in south-west England, where they employed seven servants.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=19}} The family's fortune stemmed from Ambrose's father Charles Lethbridge, who had married the wealthy coal heiress Susan Anne Yarburgh.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=19}} Neither Charles nor Ambrose had to earn a living, and as gentlemen of "independent means" spent their time engaged in rural hobbies.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=19–20}} By 1907 the Lethbridge family had moved to Lewell Lodge, [[Dorchester, Dorset|Dorchester]] in Dorset, where Violet gave birth to daughter Jacintha in June.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=20}} They then moved to a house named Trevissome in [[Flushing, Cornwall|Flushing]], Cornwall, where a second son, Ambrose "Bill" William Speke Lethbridge, was born.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=20}} Thomas' father Ambrose contracted [[tuberculosis]] at the end of the decade, resulting in the family moving into Charles' house in [[Heytesbury]], Wiltshire, where Ambrose died in September 1909, aged 34.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=20–21}}
Around this time, Thomas developed an interest in [[archaeology]], [[entomology]], and [[ornithology]], as well as drawing.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=21}} In 1913 his family made plans for him to join the [[Royal Navy]], although he failed the entrance exam due to alleged poor eyesight.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=22}} At the outbreak of the First World War, Lethbridge was sent to [[Wellington College (Berkshire)|Wellington College]] in Berkshire, while his mother and siblings moved to [[Buckhurst]] in [[Wokingham]], Berkshire.{{sfnm|1a1=Anonymous|1y=1972|1p=448|2a1=Finneran|2y=2003|2p=107|3a1=Welbourn|3y=2011|3p=23}} In February 1919 Violet and her children moved to Manor House in [[Finchampstead]], where Jacintha and Bill became seriously ill [[1918 flu pandemic|as a result of a flu pandemic]]; the former survived but Bill died in March.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=24}}
===University and Jan Mayen: 1921–23=== In October 1921 Lethbridge enrolled at [[Trinity College, Cambridge]], intent on studying geology and geography. Finding geology to be "crushingly dull", he rarely attended lectures and took little interest in his studies, instead spending much of his time shooting, fishing, and sailing. He graduated with a [[Third-class degree#Third-class honours|third class]] BA in June 1923.{{sfnm|1a1=Finneran|1y=2003|1p=107|2a1=Welbourn|2y=2011|2pp=24–26, 41}}
[[File:Beerenberg Jan Mayen.JPG|left|thumb|250px|Lethbridge was part of the first expedition to climb the Beerenberg, pictured.]]
During his studies Lethbridge decided to join an expedition to visit [[Jan Mayen]] island in the [[Arctic Circle]], alongside fellow Cambridge students James Chaworth-Musters and William Syer Bristowe and a don from [[St. John's College, Cambridge]], the geologist [[James Wordie]].{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=28–29}} Although initially planning to travel independently, they decided to join a Norwegian expedition led by Hagbord Ekerold and accompanied by Swiss mountaineer and glaciologist [[Paul Louis Mercanton]].{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=29}} The expedition set sail from [[Bratvaag]] aboard two ships in August 1921, and upon arriving at Jan Mayen they became the first team to successfully climb the [[Beerenberg]].{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=29–33}} During the expedition, Lethbridge was also able to explore his growing interest in archaeology by [[excavation (archaeology)|excavating]] at an abandoned [[Eskimo]] settlement.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=34}} ''[[The Times]]'' recognised the expedition as the mountaineering event of the year.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=34}}
At Cambridge, Lethbridge had entered into a romantic relationship with Sylvia Robertson, a clergyman's daughter, and they were engaged to be married in March 1922.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=62}} In mid-1922 he went on a sailing voyage around the [[Hebrides]] in Scotland with his fellow Trinity student Geoffrey Walford.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=41–42}} In summer 1923 Lethbridge was part of a second expedition led by Wordie, designed to explore the eastern coast of [[Greenland]] to conduct geological and archaeological investigations and repeat [[Edward Sabine]]'s pendulum gravity experiments. Sailing from [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], they stopped first at [[Bergen]] and then Jan Meyen before getting stuck in [[drift ice|pack ice]]. With food reserves running low, the crew resorted to killing and eating [[grey seals]] and [[polar bear]]s, before they eventually aborted the mission and returned home.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=35–39}}
==Archaeological career==
===Becoming Keeper of Anglo-Saxon Antiquities: 1923–47=== During his student years, Lethbridge had frequented the [[Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology, University of Cambridge|Cambridge University Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology]], where he had befriended its curator, [[L.C.G. Clarke|Louis Clarke]].{{sfnm|1a1=Finneran|1y=2003|1p=107|2a1=Welbourn|2y=2011|2pp=49–50}} Upon Lethbridge's graduation, Clarke offered him the honorary position of Keeper of Anglo-Saxon Antiquities at the museum. Lethbridge took up the voluntary and unpaid post, being able to subsist on his family's finances.{{sfnm|1a1=Finneran|1y=2003|1p=108|2a1=Welbourn|2y=2011|2p=50}} There, Lethbridge befriended the archaeologist [[Cyril Fox]], aiding in Fox's excavation of the [[Devil's Dyke, Cambridgeshire|Devil's Dyke]] in Cambridgeshire.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=52–54}} Lethbridge's archaeological excavations were however deemed of poor quality by many of his peers.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=60}} In turn, Lethbridge derided the archaeological establishment, being frustrated by how long it took them to accept what he deemed to be "facts", and he believed in focusing on what he believed to be [[instinct]] and [[common sense]].{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=60}} There were exceptions to his scorn; for instance, he developed a friendship with [[T. D. Kendrick]], an Anglo-Saxon art historian who then worked as Keeper of the [[British Museum]] in London.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=128}} Over the course of his career at the museum, Lethbridge produced 60 archaeological reports, written in an unusually informal manner that used humour and wit and included narrative descriptions of the excavation process.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=77–79}}
[[File:Museum of Archeology and Anthropology, Cambridge.jpg|thumb|left|Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology]]
In February 1924, Lethbridge married Sylvia Robertson in a ceremony held at [[Salisbury Cathedral]].{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=62–63}} Together they moved into a house known as The Lodge in [[Waterbeach]].{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=63}} There, their first two sons were born: Christopher John in March 1925 and Hugh Periam in July 1926.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=65–66}} In 1927, they moved to Mount Blow, a house in [[Great Shelford|Shelford]] designed by architect [[Edwin Lutyens]].{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=66}} It was there that Sylvia gave birth to a daughter, Belinda Mary, in April 1930.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=67}} Sylvia suffered from mental illness however, resulting in repeated hospitalisation.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=67, 75}} Lethbridge meanwhile devoted much of his time to yachting around the British Isles, sometimes taking family members with him.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=67–71}} Over the course of the 1930s he self-published a series of books featuring his own sketches and engravings of maritime scenes.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=71}} He also deepened his interest in the [[paranormal]] during this period, coming to believe that an acquaintance of his was a genuine [[psychic]] and observing an [[unidentified flying object]] in [[Bracknell]].{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=72–75, 77}}
In 1937, Wordie organised an expedition to North West Greenland to investigate [[cosmic radiation]] at high latitudes and great altitudes. He assembled a team of ten men, nine of whom were from Cambridge University, among them Lethbridge and two other archaeologists.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=81}} Setting sail in June 1937, Lethbridge undertook excavations of Eskimo sites at [[Rhyder Island]], [[Cary Island]], [[North West Island]], and [[Isbjörn Island]].{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=82–83}} On returning home in October 1937, it was decided that various geographical features encountered would be named after team members, and thus two lakes on [[Baffin Island]] were named the Lethbridge Lakes.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=83–85}} During the trip, Lethbridge became particularly interested in the design of Eskimo boats, resulting in the self-publication of his 11-page booklet, ''Umiak – the European Ancestry of the 'Women's Boat''', in 1937.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=86–87}} He followed this with a second book, ''The Fishermen of Durness'' (1938), in which he argued that a study of contemporary traditional fishing communities could inform archaeologists more about ancient boat-making and fishing.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=88}}
As the Second World War loomed, the British Admiralty commissioned Lethbridge to undertake a reconnaissance mission to Iceland to analyse German naval activity around the country, which he carried out in summer 1939. Lethbridge however treated the mission with contempt, spending much of the time visiting sites that interested him, such as locations mentioned in the Icelandic Sagas.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=89–94}} Back in Britain, he self-published a short volume discussing his Icelandic journey, ''News from Tili''.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=96}} As war broke out, Lethbridge organised the transfer of much of the museum's collections to [[Balsham Caves]] for safe keeping, while also becoming a warden of the [[Air Raid Precautions]].{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=95–96}} He also led the rescue excavation of ten prehistoric [[tumuli]] that were being destroyed to enable the construction of [[Snailwell Airfield]] for the [[Royal Air Force]].{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=96–97}}
Meanwhile, Lethbridge's wife Sylvia had been having affairs with various men, and he himself had begun an affair with Sylvia's younger cousin Mina, who was a secretary at the museum. The couple divorced in June 1943, and in November Lethbridge sold Mount Blow to pay a settlement to Sylvia.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=97–100}} He married Mina in July 1944 at [[Oban]], and together they moved from Cambridge to a farm on the Scottish island of [[Kerrera]], where Lethbridge excavated some local caves. But the couple found life on Kerrera too isolated and soon returned to Cambridge,{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=101–102}} despite Lethbridge's dislike of the place and most of the university staff whom he worked alongside.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=114–115}} He nevertheless continued his archaeological investigations, excavating an Anglo-Saxon cemetery at [[Lackford]] on Cavenham Heath, and involving himself in the investigation of the newly unearthed [[Mildenhall Treasure]], being the individual responsible for locating its probable discovery spot.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=102–115}} He was among the first to take an interest in the [[Burial in Anglo-Saxon England|cemeteries of the Mid Anglo-Saxon period]], believing that the lack of 'pagan' objects such as weapons reflected the fact that those buried in two seventh-century cemeteries were among the earliest Anglo-Saxon Christians.{{sfn|Geake|1992|p=84}} In January 1948, Lethbridge received word that his son Hugh had committed suicide after suffering [[post-traumatic stress disorder]] during his time in the armed forces.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=116–117}}
===Major publications and Gogmagog: 1948–57=== 1948 also saw the publication of Lethbridge's first major book, ''Merlin's Island: Essays on Britain in the Dark Ages'', a collection of six essays on various elements of Early Medieval Britain. Representing Lethbridge's unorthodox and eclectic approach, it was aimed at a popular rather than academic audience, and although some academic reviewers were critical, it received much qualified praise.{{sfnm|1a1=Finneran|1y=2003|1p=108|2a1=Welbourn|2y=2011|2pp=116–121}} This was followed in 1950 by ''Herdsman and Hermits: Celtic Seafarers in the Northern Sea'', in which he returned to his interest in seafaring and boats. Containing a foreword by Kendrick, it was published by [[Bowes and Bowes]].{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=128–131, 135}} In 1952, Lethbridge published ''Coast Wise Craft'', which again looked at boat building but was aimed at a general rather than specialist readership.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=131–133}} That same year, [[Thames and Hudson]] published Lethbridge's ''Boats and Boatmen'' as part of their "The Past in the Present" series edited by archaeologist [[Jacquetta Hawkes]].{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=133}} In 1954, [[Andrew Melrose]] published Lethbridge's ''The Painted Men'', a book about the [[Picts]] of Northern Britain. It was deemed to be his last conventional book within the archaeological and academic community.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=143–146}} As part of his increasing public profile, the [[BBC]] invited him to give the third talk in their second series of ''Myth or Legend?'', which he devoted to the question of whether Europeans had arrived in the Americas prior to [[Christopher Columbus]]; in particular he looked at the claims that [[St. Brendan]] and [[Thorfinn Karlsefni]] had made the journey across the Atlantic.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=134–135}} Over several seasons he also carried out excavations of wheelhouses at [[South Uist]], and on one occasion was visited at the site by Queen [[Elizabeth II]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]].{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=141–143}}
Lethbridge's next project focused on searching for a chalk [[hill figure]] that was reported to have once existed on [[Wandlebury Hill]] in the [[Gog Magog Hills]], Cambridgeshire. Towards the end of 1954 he began investigating the site, inserting metal rods into the ground to determine where he believed the turf had once been removed to expose the chalk below. He believed that he had revealed three large figures, a warrior, a hooded goddess, and a sun god, asserting them to be likely 3000 years old, and then began excavation to remove the turf and reveal the figures.{{sfnm|1a1=Finneran|1y=2003|1p=109|2a1=Welbourn|2y=2011|2pp=147–151|3a1=Gibson|3y=2013|3pp=93–94}} Lethbridge sought much publicity for his discovery, reporting on it to ''[[The Times]]'' and being interviewed by the ''[[London Evening News]]''.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=152–153}} However, many archaeologists were sceptical of Lethbridge's methodology and the existence of the hill figures; they believed that the soft patches of chalk were the result of chalk solifluction and were only interpreted as human-made figures through Lethbridge's vivid imagination.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=151}} The [[Council for British Archaeology]] brought together a committee to assess Lethbridge's findings, composed of I. W. Cornwall, [[W. F. Grimes]], [[Christopher Hawkes]], and [[Stuart Piggott]]. With the aid of geologist [[F. E. Zeuner]], the committee concluded that the shapes Lethbridge had discovered were natural, having been formed during the last [[Ice Age]]. However, Hawkes disagreed with his colleagues, and believed that while not proven, Lethbridge's conclusions could not be disproved.{{sfnm|1a1=Finneran|1y=2003|1p=109|2a1=Welbourn|2y=2011|2pp=152–154}} Lethbridge stuck by his original ideas, and wrote a book aimed at a general audience, ''Gogmagog – The Buried Gods'' on the basis of them. It was published by Routledge and Kegan Paul in 1957, but received no supportive reviews.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=154–157, 160–161}} In May 1957, the Egyptologist [[Margaret Murray]] involved herself in the [[Gogmagog (folklore)|Gogmagog]] debate, championing Lethbridge's ideas against the academic fraternity in a letter she sent to ''[[The Times]]''. W. F. Grimes responded by claiming that she was out of touch with contemporary scholarship.{{sfnm|1a1=Welbourn|1y=2010|1p=40|2a1=Welbourn|2y=2011|2pp=157–159, 164–165}}
==Later life==
===Embracing parapsychology: 1957–64===
{{Quote box|width=25em|align=right|quote="There is really only one study of man, and this should be known as Anthropology. Medical Science, History, Archaeology, Folk Lore and the rest are all branches of the one study. But this present age is one of specialization and all the branches are tending to become so elaborate and, at the same time, so constricted that we are in need of trained middle-men, who have a wide enough grasp of all of them to pull the whole thing together and present it in a readable form to those who wish to learn."|source=— T.C. Lethbridge, 1962.{{sfn|Lethbridge|1962|p=ix}} }}
As a result of the widespread rejection of his ''Gogmagog'' claims, Lethbridge became increasingly critical of the academic and professional archaeological community, believing that an attitude of what he called "trade unionism" had caused most archaeologists to reject independent thought. As a result, he decided to resign and move away from Cambridge in late 1957.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=163–164}} Relocating to [[Branscombe]] in southern [[Devon]], he and Mina set up home in Hole House, a fortified building that dated to the Early Modern period,{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=164, 197}} and angered some of the locals by banning [[fox hunting|fox hunters]] from crossing his land.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=259}} Lethbridge came to believe that Hole House was haunted, describing unexplained noises and smells there; this increased his interest in the paranormal, and he decided to devote much of his time to investigating such phenomena in what he deemed to be a scientific manner.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=198–200}} Lethbridge believed that ghosts were [[Stone Tape|projections stored in rock]] and other material substances and which echoed particularly emotional or traumatic events that either happened in the past or will happen in the future.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=203}} He focused many of his experiments on [[dowsing]] using a [[pendulum]], coming to believe that the length of string used and the number of oscillations could be used to determine the type of object being detected.{{sfnm|1a1=Finneran|1y=2003|1p=110|2a1=Welbourn|2y=2011|2pp=208–212}}
His first book on the subject of what he often termed "the odd" was ''Ghost and Ghoul'', published in 1961 by Routledge and Kegan Paul.{{sfnm|1a1=Finneran|1y=2003|1p=110|2a1=Welbourn|2y=2011|2pp=213–222}} In this work he argued that the [[mind]] was separate from the brain; he believed that the mind was connected to an ancestral collective mind which everyone inherited. Many of the ideas expressed in the work were akin to those of [[Carl Jung]], [[Richard Semon]], and [[Amy Warburg]], although it is not clear if Lethbridge had been aware of this beforehand.{{sfnm|1a1=Finneran|1y=2003|1p=110|2a1=Welbourn|2y=2011|2pp=213–222}} An extract was subsequently published in the January 1963 edition of ''[[Fantastic (magazine)|Fantastic Stories of Imagination]]''.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=229}} He followed this work with ''Witches – Investigating an Ancient Religion'' (1962), which articulated a form of Murray's [[witch-cult hypothesis]] but also contained many digressions and anecdotes unrelated to that topic.{{sfnm|1a1=Finneran|1y=2003|1p=110|2a1=Welbourn|2y=2011|2pp=223, 226}} Returning to the themes present in ''Ghost and Ghoul'', Lethbridge published ''Ghost and Divining Rod'' in 1963, in which he discussed his progress with his pendulum experiments.{{sfnm|1a1=Finneran|1y=2003|1p=110|2a1=Welbourn|2y=2011|2pp=231–233}} On the basis of this, the BBC filmed a short documentary titled ''Ghost Hunting with T.C. Lethbridge'' in May 1964, in which Lethbridge was filmed repeating his pendulum experiences in his garden.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=234–237}}
===Final years: 1965–71===
Lethbridge's next book was ''ESP – Beyond Time and Distance'', published in 1965. It dealt with the theme of [[extra-sensory perception]] and articulated Lethbridge's argument that rays of energy were transmitted from every object, and that they could be detected using pendulum dowsing.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=238–239}} In 1966 he published ''A Step in the Dark'', which repeated many of his theories regarding pendulum dowsing present in earlier works.{{sfnm|1a1=Finneran|1y=2003|1p=110|2a1=Welbourn|2y=2011|2p=242}} Early that year, Lethbridge first began struggling against [[heart disease]], an affliction that had resulted from his obesity.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=240}} In both his books and private letters from this period he regularly ranted against modern life and society, while in other correspondences with individuals in the United States he championed the authenticity of the [[Kensington Runestone]] and [[Westford Knight]].{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=244–258}}
In 1969, Lethbridge published ''The Monkey's Tail'', in which he discussed [[Darwinian]] evolution. Although agreeing that the evolution of species was an objective fact, he nevertheless argued that there was a blueprint for existence and that [[Genetic memory (biology)|genetic memory]] was a reality.{{sfnm|1a1=Finneran|1y=2003|1p=110|2a1=Welbourn|2y=2011|2pp=260–261}} In a sequel published in 1969, ''The Legend of the Sons of God – A Fantasy?'', Lethbridge argued that extraterrestrials had been responsible for aiding Earth's evolutionary development. Echoing many of the claims made by [[Erich von Däniken]] in ''[[Chariots of the Gods]]'' (1968), Lethbridge argued that the [[Stone circles in the British Isles and Brittany|late prehistoric stone circles of the British Isles]] had been beacons for extraterrestrial spacecraft.{{sfnm|1a1=Finneran|1y=2003|1p=110|2a1=Welbourn|2y=2011|2pp=267–271}} In this, his work has been cited as an anticipation of the [[Earth mysteries]] movement that expanded across Britain in the following decade.{{sfn|Finneran|2003|pp=109–110}}
Lethbridge's heart condition worsened, to the extent that he was unable to attend his mother's funeral in 1970.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=272}} He eventually required 24-hour care, and was transferred to [[Nuffield Hospital]] in [[Exeter]], where he died in his sleep on 30 September 1971.{{sfnm|1a1=Anonymous|1y=1972|1p=448|2a1=Welbourn|2y=2011|2p=274}} His body was interred at the family plot in [[Heytesbury]], Wiltshire.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=274}} As the Branscombe house was owned by the Lethbridge Family Trust, Mina was obliged to move out after her husband's death, and she sold his belongings out of financial necessity.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=275}} Mina also collected together Lethbridge's unfinished book with the help of writer [[Colin Wilson]]; together they assembled it into publishable form and it was brought out by Routledge in 1976 as ''The Power of the Pendulum''.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|pp=275–276}}
==Reception and legacy==
{{Quote box|width=25em|align=right|quote="The death of T. C. Lethbridge in the early autumn of last year took away from us a man who had been a colourful, stimulating, provocative and often controversial figure in British archaeology; a man who could very properly be described, in Cyrus Gordon’s phrase, as one who throughout his life kept an open mind and avoided confusing majority opinion with truth."|source=— Glyn Daniel, 1972.{{sfn|Daniel|1972|p=5}} }}
Archaeologist [[Niall Finneran]] asserted that Lethbridge had a "distinguished if fairly unspectacular reputation" within British archaeology prior to his adoption of fringe theories.{{sfn|Finneran|2003|p=108}} Various colleagues expressed critical praise of his work in this field; for instance, Lethbridge's fellow Anglo-Saxon archaeologist [[Audrey Meaney]] noted that his "observations on features in the cemeteries he excavated around Cambridge were perspicacious but in advance of his time".{{sfn|Meaney|1981|p=37}} Another Anglo-Saxon archaeologist, Sam Lucy, later noted that Lethbridge's observation that those buried with Anglo-Saxon material culture need not have been ethnically descended from continental migrants was &ndash; while largely ignored by his contemporaries &ndash; widely accepted in scholarship by the end of the 20th century.{{sfn|Lucy|2000|p=173}} However, his embrace of unorthodox and pseudo-scientific views later led to professional archaeologists becoming increasingly critical of his work; as his biographer Terry Welbourn noted, Lethbridge's peers came to view him as being "too radical&nbsp;... a loose cannon and maverick".{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=13}}
On his death, [[Glyn Daniel]] described Lethbridge as "a colourful, stimulating, provocative and often controversial figure in British archaeology", who represented "one of the last of that invaluable band of dilettante scholars and devoted amateurs of whom we have had so many in Britain".{{sfn|Daniel|1972|p=5}} Although stating that Lethbridge only emerged as a "semi-professional" for a "short time", he praised much of Lethbridge's writing for its "freshness and an eager restless sense of enquiry".{{sfn|Daniel|1972|p=5}} An anonymously authored obituary in ''[[Society of Antiquaries of London|The Antiquaries Journal]]'' referred to "the strength and honesty of Lethbridge's character as a man, and the singleness of purpose that united all his work, as experimental testing of what he found by observation", seeing these as the unifying characteristics behind his divergent research interests.{{sfn|Anonymous|1972|p=449}} According to the historian [[Ronald Hutton]], as a result of both his unorthodox ideas and his "contempt for professionalism in all fields", Lethbridge's "status as a scholar never really rose above that of an unusually lively local antiquary".{{sfn|Hutton|1999|p=274}} His books continue to be largely ignored by academics into the 21st century.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=16}}
Describing Lethbridge as "one of the most compelling" figures in 20th-century British archaeology,{{sfn|Finneran|2003|p=107}} Finneran believed that at the start of the 21st century, Lethbridge was best known for his advocacy of dowsing.{{sfn|Finneran|2003|p=107}} As such, Finneran asserted that Lethbridge's "true legacy" lay outside of "conventional archaeology", and could instead be located within the Earth mysteries movement.{{sfn|Finneran|2003|p=112}} Lethbridge's work continued to attract interest from parapsychologists after his death. The author [[MB Devot|M.B. Devot]] drew heavily on Ghost and Ghoul in his ''Spirits of Field and Hearth''.<ref name="ForteanTimes53">''Fortean Times'' No.53 ''MB Devot, A Life in the Hedgerow''</ref> In 1978, the author [[Colin Wilson]] devoted part one of his book ''Mysteries'' to a discussion of Lethbridge's ideas.{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=276}} In 2003, a group of admirers of his work calling themselves "The Sons of T.C. Lethbridge" (Doggen Foster, Kevlar Bales and Welbourn Tekh), with the aid of Wilson and [[Julian Cope]], released ''A Giant: The Definitive T.C. Lethbridge'', a set comprising a booklet and two CDs containing music accompanying discussions of Lethbridge's work.<ref>[[Julian Cope|Cope, Julian]] (2003). "Bring It On!" in ''A Giant: The Definitive T.C. Lethbridge'' booklet. Lincoln: Aegir Recording Company.</ref> Welbourn subsequently published a biography of Lethbridge in 2011, titled ''T.C. Lethbridge: The Man who Saw the Future''; in it, he expressed his view that the archaeologist was "one of the most remarkable, yet overlooked men of the twentieth century".{{sfn|Welbourn|2011|p=13}}
